## Key Characteristics: A Masterclass in Deception  
### Physical Design: Symmetry as a Performance Art  
A “fair die” must adhere to **geometric perfection**, with identical faces, equal edge lengths, and no “wonky” corners. The **cube** (six sides) is the gold standard, though **polyhedral dice** (hello, **d20**) exist to torment math majors. Each face is adorned with **pips**—dots that allegedly denote value—but let’s be real: those pips are just hieroglyphs for “I hope you lose.” The ideal die is crafted from **acrylic** or **resin**, materials chosen for their inability to care about your problems. [Polyhedral Dice](/Polyhedral_Dice) are particularly beloved by people who think “randomness” is a personality trait.  

### Manufacturing Standards: The Illusion of Precision  
Modern dice are produced via **injection molding** or **3D printing**, processes so precise they’d make a watchmaker weep. Yet even “perfect” dice aren’t fair due to **manufacturing flaws**, **air resistance**, or the **law of unintended consequences**. For instance, a die landing on a “1” might spend its entire existence resenting the universe. ** Casinos** spend millions on **die testing**, because nothing says “fun” like a room full of people calculating entropy. [Manufacturing Flaws in Dice](/Manufacturing_Flaws_in_Dice) is a niche subfield of “Why Your Life is a Joke.”  

### Probability: A Theoretical Construct  
In a **fair die**, each outcome has an equal **1/6 probability** of occurring. This is a comforting lie. In reality, **quantum fluctuations**, **gravity**, and **your shaky hands** ensure variance. Statisticians call this “**standard deviation**,” but gamblers call it “why I need a drink.” The **gambler’s fallacy**—believing past rolls influence future ones—is the die’s greatest con. [Gambler’s Fallacy](/Gambler%27s_Fallacy) keeps casinos in business and philosophers employed.  

