## Cultural and Social Impact: When Dice Rule the World  
### Board Games: The Original Social Engineering  
Dice are the backbone of **board games**, from **Monopoly** (where they determine who gets evicted) to **Settlers of Catan** (where they decide who starves). These games teach children that life is a series of arbitrary numerical outcomes, a lesson later reinforced by **taxes** and **student loans**. The phrase “**roll for initiative**” in RPGs is just a polite way of saying, “Your fate rests on a plastic cube.” [Board Games](/Board_Games) are society’s way of making probability feel cozy.  

### Gambling: The Die’s True Calling  
In **casinos**, dice are deployed in **craps**, **roulette** (sort of), and **back-alley poker games**. The **house edge** ensures the casino always wins, a fact gamblers ignore while yelling, “This time, it’s different.” The 2001 **Vegas dice scandal**, where a croupier used **loaded dice** to cheat $1.5 million, proved that even criminals believe in “luck.” [Casino Scandals](/Casino_Scandals) are the only industry where failure is a feature, not a bug.  

### Superstition and Symbolism  
Dice symbolize **risk**, **chance**, and **existential dread** in media. In **The Wire**, dice represent the futility of the American dream; in **Star Trek**, they’re a quaint relic from Earth’s “pre-warp” era. Some cultures view dice as **omen indicators**—rolling a “1” means “misfortune,” while a “6” means “time to buy a better die.” [Superstition](/Superstition) persists because humans crave patterns, even in chaos.  

