## Modern Relevance: Why We Still Use These Things  
### The Rise of Digital Dice  
**Random Number Generators (RNGs)** in video games and apps have largely replaced physical dice, but purists insist on **tactile suffering**. **Tabletop RPGs** like *D&D* still cling to dice, partly because typing “you stab the dragon” is less satisfying than rolling a **natural 20**. **Cryptographic RNGs**, meanwhile, use dice-based algorithms—because even computers need to pretend they’re not all-powerful. [Random Number Generators](/Random_Number_Generators) are the digital world’s attempt to replicate a flaw only humans could invent.  

### Nostalgia and the board game renaissance  
The **board game renaissance** of the 2010s saw dice make a comeback, now marketed as “vintage charm” or “analog authenticity.” Games like **Wingspan** and **Gloomhaven** use dice not for randomness, but to mask the fact that players are just rolling to see how long they can delay adulthood. [Board Game Renaissance](/Board_Game_Renaissance) is capitalism’s way of saying, “Pay $80 for a box of plastic cubes.”  

